{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"a3400d26-cbd6-47f6-af03-bb8e9692145a","content":"Here are the MSBuild evaluation performance issues in this project:\n\n---\n\n**1. Deeply chained `<Import>` statements** (lines 6 in `.csproj`, `level1.props` → `level2.props` → `level3.props`)\n\nThree levels of nested imports forces MSBuild to resolve and parse each file sequentially during evaluation. In larger projects this pattern scales poorly and hurts IDE responsiveness.\n\n**2. Recursive glob with `**\\*.*`** (line 9 in `.csproj`)\n\n```xml\n<AdditionalFiles Include=\"**\\*.*\" Exclude=\"**\\bin\\**;**\\obj\\**\" />\n```\n\nThis walks the entire directory tree during every evaluation pass. It's one of the most common causes of slow evaluation — especially on large repos or network drives.\n\n**3. Property function reading a file at evaluation time** (line 13 in `.csproj`)\n\n```xml\n<BuildNotes>$([System.IO.File]::ReadAllText('build-notes.txt'))</BuildNotes>\n```\n\nCalling `System.IO.File.ReadAllText` inside a property forces synchronous file I/O during evaluation. This blocks the evaluation engine and cannot be cached or parallelized.\n\n---\n\n### Recommendations\n\n| Issue | Fix |\n|-------|-----|\n| Deep imports | Flatten into a single `.props` or use the SDK's standard `Directory.Build.props` |\n| `**\\*.*` glob | Narrow the pattern (e.g., `**\\*.cs`) or move to an explicit item list |\n| `File::ReadAllText` | Move to a target that runs at build time, or use `ReadLinesFromFile` task |\n\nThe recursive glob and the file-read property function are the biggest offenders — both execute on every evaluation (including every IDE keystroke that triggers re-evaluation).","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"13183685-7683-4b64-a08e-a5011aa715a7","outputTokens":434,"requestId":"2841:71DA5:2D023F:3474A0:69FA95F3"},"id":"0fbc74a4-ba92-43ca-84c9-0c1eb3618853","timestamp":"2026-05-06T01:14:38.706Z","parentId":"06de41cd-748d-4ce0-b980-7ccc1eac3321"}
